## Communication Mechanisms

### 1. Extension ↔ Web App (window.postMessage + chrome.runtime)

**Documentation:** [Message passing | Chrome for Developers](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/develop/concepts/messaging)

**How It Works:**

```
Web Page (Neuman Brain)
    ↓ window.postMessage()
Content Script (injected by extension)
    ↓ chrome.runtime.sendMessage()
Background Script (service worker)
    ↓ (processes bookmarks)
    ↓ chrome.runtime.sendMessage() back
Content Script
    ↓ window.postMessage() back
Web Page (Neuman Brain) → IndexedDB
```

**Key APIs:**
- `window.postMessage(data, targetOrigin)` - Web page → content script
- `chrome.runtime.sendMessage(message, callback)` - Content script → background
- `chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener()` - Listen for messages
- `chrome.runtime.connect()` - Long-lived connection (for streaming)

**Security:**
- MUST validate `message.origin` before processing (prevent spoofing)
- Use `externally_connectable` in manifest to whitelist domains
- Never blindly trust messages from web pages

**Sources:**
- [Message passing | Chrome for Developers](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/develop/concepts/messaging)
- [Is it allowed to use window.postMessage() in a chrome extension? - Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40657564/is-it-allowed-to-use-window-postmessage-in-a-chrome-extension)
- [Message Passing & Security in Chrome Extensions | Duo Security](https://duo.com/labs/tech-notes/message-passing-and-security-considerations-in-chrome-extensions)

