### 2. Native Messaging (Alternative)

**Documentation:** [Native messaging - Mozilla | MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Add-ons/WebExtensions/Native_messaging)

**How It Works:**
- Extension communicates with native desktop application
- Uses stdin/stdout with JSON messages
- Native app must be registered with manifest file
- Extension requires `"nativeMessaging"` permission

**Message Format:**
- UTF-8 encoded JSON
- Prefixed with 32-bit message length (native byte order)
- Max size: 1MB (extension → native), 64MB (native → extension)

**Use Cases:**
- Password managers (native app stores encrypted passwords)
- Hardware access (e.g., smart cards)
- OS-level integrations

**Why NOT for Neuman Brain:**
- Too complex (requires native app installation)
- Goes against web-first philosophy
- No benefit over direct Bookmarks API access
- Maintenance burden (multiple OS builds)

**Sources:**
- [Native messaging - Mozilla - MDN Web Docs](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Add-ons/WebExtensions/Native_messaging)
- [Native messaging | Chrome for Developers](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/develop/concepts/native-messaging)

