## Competitor Analysis

### Raindrop.io

**Documentation:** [Browser Extension ― Raindrop.io Help](https://help.raindrop.io/browser-extension)

**Architecture:** ☁️ Cloud-based (NOT browser API sync)

**Key Findings:**
- **Cloud-First:** All bookmarks stored on Raindrop.io servers (not local)
- **NO Browser Sync:** Does not sync with browser's native bookmarks
- **Manual Only:** User must use Raindrop extension to save bookmarks (browser's "Add bookmark" ignored)
- **Real-Time:** Syncs across devices via cloud (requires internet)
- **Open Source:** Apps are open source (community can examine)

**Implications for Neuman Brain:**
- Raindrop AVOIDS browser bookmarks API entirely (separate system)
- We have opportunity to do BETTER by actually syncing browser bookmarks
- Their approach goes against local-first philosophy (server required)

**Sources:**
- [Browser Extension ― Raindrop.io Help](https://help.raindrop.io/browser-extension)
- [Bookmarks ― Raindrop.io Help](https://help.raindrop.io/bookmarks)
- [full sync with chrome and safari | Feature request | Raindrop.io](https://raindropio.canny.io/feature-requests/p/full-sync-with-chrome-and-safari)

### Pocket (Mozilla)

**Architecture:** ☁️ Cloud-based + browser integration

**Key Findings:**
- Native integration with Firefox (built-in)
- Extension for Chrome/Edge
- Cloud sync (Mozilla servers)
- Focuses on "read later" not bookmark management

### Notion Web Clipper

**Architecture:** ☁️ Extension saves to Notion cloud

**Key Findings:**
- Captures page content, not bookmarks
- Saves to Notion workspace (cloud)
- No sync with browser bookmarks

**Conclusion:** NO competitors actually sync browser bookmarks locally. This is our blue ocean opportunity!

