### Approach 2: File System Access API (Manual)

**Architecture:**

```
Browser Bookmark File (Disk)
    ↓ (User manually selects via file picker)
File System Access API
    ↓ (Reads file contents)
Neuman Brain Web App (Parser)
    ↓ (Parses JSON or SQLite)
IndexedDB (Link Library Store)
```

**How It Works:**
1. User clicks "Import from Browser" in NB
2. File picker opens (File System Access API)
3. User navigates to bookmark file location
4. NB reads file and parses
5. Bookmarks imported to Link Library

**Pros:**
✅ No extension needed
✅ Simple implementation
✅ Works immediately (no store approval)
✅ No permissions dialog (beyond file picker)

**Cons:**
❌ **Manual process** (defeats "automatic sync" goal)
❌ **One-time import** (not continuous sync)
❌ **Chrome-only** (Firefox/Safari don't support)
❌ **Read-only** (cannot write back to browser)
❌ User must know file locations
❌ File may be locked while browser open
❌ Different formats per browser (Chrome JSON vs Firefox SQLite)

**Development Effort:** ~16 hours
- File picker UI: 4 hours
- Chrome JSON parser: 4 hours
- Firefox SQLite parser: 6 hours (more complex)
- Testing: 2 hours

**Privacy:**
✅ No network access
✅ User explicitly grants access
⚠️ File remains readable (no encryption)

**Verdict:** Too manual, doesn't meet requirements. Better than nothing but not ideal.

